rsistent concerns, especially those relating to language, knowledge, and the workings of tragic theater itself. James Barrett gives close readings of several plays including Aeschylus's Persians, Sophocles' Electra and Oedipus Tyrannus, and Euripides' Bacchae and Rhesos. He traces the literary ancestry of the tragic messenger, showing that the messenger's narrative constitutes an unexplored site of engagement with Homeric epic, and that the role illuminates fifth-century b.c. experimentation with modes of speech. Breaking new ground in the study of Athenian tragedy, Barrett deepens our understanding of many central texts and of a form of theater that highlights the fragility and limits of human knowledge, a theme explored by its use of the messenger.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGreek drama (Tragedy)xHistory and criticism. 0aMessengers in literature. 0aNarration (Rhetoric)xHistoryyTo 1500. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aachilles.  aaeschylus.  aancient greece.  aancient world.  aarete.  aathenian tragedy.  abacchae.  aclassicism.  adrama.  aelectra.  aepic.  aepistemology.  aeuripides.  agenre study.  agods and goddesses.  agreek tragedy.  ahellenism.  ahomer.  ahomeric epic.  ahubris.  ahuman knowledge.  aliterary ancestry.  aliterary criticism.  aliterature.  amessenger.  amythology.  anarrative poetics.  anarrative theory.  anonfiction.  aoedipus rex.  aoedipus tyrannus.  aoedipus.  aperforming arts.  apersians.  apoetry.  arhesos.  arhetoric.  arhetorical analysis.  asophocles.  atheater.  atragedy.  atragic messenger.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz